article.headline: Lady Techsters win third title in as many years
article.linkText: Louisiana Tech wins WAC, 23rd straight tourney bid
article.story:
FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- With three titles in three years, Louisiana Tech clearly is the class of the Western Athletic Conference. Now the Lady Techsters will find out how much that means to the rest of college basketball.

Amisha Carter had 22 points and 16 rebounds, Erica Smith-Taylor
added 22 points and Louisiana Tech (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) won its third straight WAC tournament, beating Rice 76-52 Saturday.

Tasha Crain scored nine points for the Lady Techsters (27-2),
who won their 19th straight game with more of the athletic defense
that defines the program. With six steals apiece by Carter and
Smith-Taylor, they earned their 23rd straight trip to the NCAA
tournament.

"I was just trying my best not to let them catch it easy,"
Smith-Taylor said. "We knew that if we played tough defense, we
could be successful."

Carter, the WAC player of the year, was named tournament MVP.
Trina Frierson, who had four points and 10 rebounds, joined
Smith-Taylor on the all-tournament team.

Louisiana Tech, the WAC's dominant team since joining the league
in 2001, has won 25 straight tournament games and nine straight
league tournament titles since the 1995 Sun Belt tourney. The
school also has won 12 straight regular-season championships in
three conferences, dating back to the 1988 American South
Conference.

But that hasn't meant much to the NCAA tournament selection
committee in recent years.

Last March, the Lady Techsters went into the tournament with 27
straight victories, a No. 6 ranking and the WAC titles from the
regular season and the conference tourney -- and they were given a
fifth seed in the West Regional, forcing them to start on the road.
Louisiana Tech advanced to the regional semifinals before losing to
LSU.

"Last year, we ran through this tournament a lot easier than we
did this year, and it didn't hurt our preparation for (the
NCAAs)," coach Kurt Budke said.

Louisiana Tech never trailed against second-seeded Rice (21-9),
the last team to beat the Lady Techsters back on Jan. 5. They
opened the second half with a 17-5 run and never let up the
pressure, even forcing turnovers in the final minutes of a blowout.

"This team is very good," Budke said. "At halftime, we didn't
have to go in there and yell and scream and shout. We just talked
about what we need to do to get better. All we had to say was that
we weren't playing to the level we want to play, come on."

Anne Peck had 10 points for Rice, which has a good chance to
make the NCAA tournament despite losing two of three to Louisiana
Tech this season, including this embarrassing defeat.

"We just didn't handle the ball well, and we didn't have
anybody step up and get some things done for us," coach Cristy
McKinney said. "They took it to us, and we kind of jumped back and
got on our heels."

Said Budke: "You cannot tell me there's 63 teams better than
Rice. There's no way. They belong in the tournament."

The Lady Owls began the season 2-5, but won 15 of their last 16
before falling apart against the Techsters' defensive pressure with
35.8 percent shooting, 29 turnovers and a 52-33 rebounding deficit.
Freshman Lauren Neaves, who made the all-tournament team, blocked
six shots but was held to eight points.

"I felt I should have been much more physical," Neaves said.
"I apologized to my teammates and coaches for not stepping it up.
... I need to get stronger. They outweighed me by, like, 30 pounds.
I need to put on some weight."

Only one thing didn't seem to go Louisiana Tech's way: A
cheerleader left the court at the Save Mart Center after she fell
awkwardly during a first-half stunt.

Tulsa's Jillian Robbins also made the all-tournament team.
